node.text:
Mark Anthony Gonzales was on his way to his BJJ school in Texas when he noticed a police officer having difficulty enacting an arrest near his house. He got out to help, while his wife recorded (for liability purposes), and the video of his BJJ-laced intervention went viral with over 20 million views in 48 hours. In this interview Mark shares details of his first-hand experience with us. 

p.s. I also spoke to the cop who graciously accepted our offer to attend a GST course for free, and he’s excited to learn. 🙏🏼🙏🏼

Link in bio to GST and the EPIC new 32 Principles t-shirt that just arrived!

node.text:
This is one of the best arrest videos I’ve ever seen! The man who intervened trains BJJ and the combination of his technique AND his calm communication with both the officer and suspect is the stuff of legends! 

If anyone knows the cop, please let him know we’re gonna sponsor him to attend GST for in person certification or online certification, 100% free. With the little training officers get, I thought he did quite well. 

If anyone knows the BJJ legend, please DM me ASAP. I want to gift him The 32 Principles. 

🔥Official Announcement: Any BJJ student who ever assists in an arrest (and the assistance is verified by video or the officer involved) will get THE 32 PRINCIPLES for free! 🔥

The32Principles.com - 25% off until midnight tonight!

We’ve gotten this question by countless police officers over the last several years and we finally came up with a solution! 

Gracie Survival Tactics (GST) is a living curriculum that is always evolving to increase each officers ability to deescalate whenever possible, and when not possible, to give them the ability to handle each encounter with the lowest level of force. 

GST is now POST Certified in 38 States and the entire Level 1 course can be completed online from anywhere in the world. The “2-for-1 Special” we’ve run since January will end on August 20, 2021, so if you’re ready to get certified, now’s the time! 

Link in bio for online certification info and upcoming live course dates!

This 68-year-old man got knocked out and robbed in New York. If anyone knows how we can get a hold of him, please DM me. 

As hard as they are to watch, videos like these are a harsh reminders that violence is a reality, and even though we aren’t required to learn self-defense, we have the right to. 

This Monday, August 9, 2021, we are launching a 10-day online self-defense course that is 100% free for anyone who wants to learn the most important fundamental self-defense skills jiu-jitsu has to offer. Once you register (link in bio) you’ll receive full access to one complete lesson per day from August 9th through August 18th. On August 19th the course will be locked and will only be available for paid purchase from the that point on. No experience is required, the course can be done solo or with a partner, and is designed to be completed from home at your own pace. 

We’ve never done this before, and we’re excited to have you join us for this 10-day jiu-jitsu immersion. 

@ryrongracie @onecommune @gracieuniversityhq

node.text:
Mark Anthony Gonzales was on his way to his BJJ school in Texas when he noticed a police officer having difficulty enacting an arrest near his house. He got out to help, while his wife recorded (for liability purposes), and the video of his BJJ-laced intervention went viral with over 20 million views in 48 hours. In this interview Mark shares details of his first-hand experience with us. 

p.s. I also spoke to the cop who graciously accepted our offer to attend a GST course for free, and he’s excited to learn. 🙏🏼🙏🏼

Link in bio to GST and the EPIC new 32 Principles t-shirt that just arrived!

node.text:
People often ask “What does ‘Gracie Survival Tactics’ mean?” 
Answer: The techniques that will help ensure the survivability of the officers AND the survivability of the civilians they serve. If a technique doesn’t do both, it’s not GST, it’s that simple.

For those who haven’t seen the full HBO segment, check it out at @gracieuniversityhq IGTV feed.

1. ASSESS the threat to the officer and to yourself. Is your help really needed? Is it even safe for you to intervene? 

2. ASK permission to help and identify yourself to the officer. An officer has no way of knowing which team you're on, so let them know you're there to help and wait for explicit permission to enter. 

3. ACKNOWLEDGE the risks of intervention. There are safety risks and there are legal risks. Each jurisdiction has different laws regarding civilian intervention so make sure you know yours. 
🙏🏼

From this day forward (no past incidents), anyone who adheres to these guidelines who lawfully and safely intervenes, I’d like to reward your efforts with access to The 32 Principles, as long as your intervention is captured on camera OR verified by the officer involved. 🙏🏼

Principle 15: Fork
Creating positional dilemmas that force your opponent to choose how they lose.
 
A forked position creates two or more “prongs” of opportunity. The Fork Principle forces your opponent to choose between a submission, sweep, takedown, pass, reversal, positional advancement, or any combination thereof. The River and Fork Principles are similar, but one is reactive and other is pro-active.  The River Principle applies to an open, free flowing situation in which you react to obstacles by flowing around them.  The Fork Principle actively limits your opponent’s options causing them to flow into positions in which you will determine the outcome.
